BT /F1 12 Tf 64 654 Td (- Abdullah Al Tamsha - 230208916) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 54 630 Td (1. Why Salting Is Necessary Against Rainbow Table Attacks) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 610 Td (Password hashing is necessary because storing plaintext passwords creates immediate) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 594 Td (risk if the database is leaked. However, hashing alone is not enough when many users) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 578 Td (may choose common passwords.) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 558 Td (A rainbow table is a precomputed lookup table of password hashes. Attackers build) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 542 Td (these tables by hashing many common passwords in advance. If a database stores) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 526 Td (unsalted hashes, the attacker can compare the stolen hashes against the rainbow) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 510 Td (table and quickly recover weak or reused passwords.) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 490 Td (Salting prevents this shortcut. A salt is a random value added to each password) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 474 Td (before hashing. Because each user gets a different salt, the same password produces) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 458 Td (a different hash for each account. This means an attacker cannot use one precomputed) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 442 Td (rainbow table against every user in the database.) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 422 Td (For example, without salts:) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 68 402 Td (password123 -> same hash for every user) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 382 Td (With unique salts:) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 68 362 Td (password123 + saltA -> hashA) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 68 346 Td (password123 + saltB -> hashB) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 326 Td (bcrypt automatically generates and stores a salt as part of the final hash string.) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 310 Td (It is also intentionally slow, which makes large-scale brute force attacks more) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 294 Td (expensive.) Tj ET
BT /F2 12 Tf 54 266 Td (2. Risks of Storing Sensitive Data Inside a JWT Payload) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 246 Td (JWT payloads are not encrypted by default. A standard JWT is only Base64URL encoded) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 230 Td (and signed. The signature proves that the token was issued by the server and has not) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 214 Td (been modified, but anyone who has the token can decode the payload and read its) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 198 Td (contents.) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 178 Td (Because of this, sensitive data should not be stored inside a JWT payload. Examples) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 54 162 Td (of data that should not be placed in a JWT include:) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 64 142 Td (- Plaintext passwords) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 64 126 Td (- Password hashes) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 64 110 Td (- Credit card numbers) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 64 94 Td (- National ID numbers) Tj ET
BT /F1 12 Tf 64 78 Td (- Secret API keys) Tj ET
endstream
